not responding normally to insulin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following molecular mechanisms is most likely contributing to insulin resistance in skeletal muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inflammatory signaling inhibiting insulin receptor substrate proteins","Endoplasmic reticulum stress from unfolded protein accumulation","Diacylglycerol-mediated activation of insulin receptor substrate proteins","Ceramide-induced activation of protein kinase B","Mitochondrial nitric oxide production from fatty acid oxidation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with poorly controlled type 2 diabetes mellitus and obesity, conditions characterised by insulin resistance. In skeletal muscle, \u003Cstrong\u003Einflammatory signaling inhibiting insulin receptor substrate proteins\u003C/strong\u003E is a key mechanism of insulin resistance. Pro-inflammatory cytokines like tumour necrosis factor alpha activate serine kinases that phosphorylate insulin receptor substrate proteins, disrupting normal insulin signalling cascades.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoplasmic reticulum stress from unfolded protein accumulation\u003C/strong\u003E can contribute to insulin resistance, but this mechanism is more prominent in liver and adipose tissue rather than skeletal muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiacylglycerol-mediated activation of insulin receptor substrate proteins\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because diacylglycerol actually impairs insulin signalling by activating protein kinase C, which inhibits insulin receptor substrate proteins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeramide-induced activation of protein kinase B\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because ceramides inhibit rather than activate protein kinase B (Akt), contributing to insulin resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitochondrial nitric oxide production from fatty acid oxidation\u003C/strong\u003E may play a role in insulin resistance but is not the primary mechanism in skeletal muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these molecular mechanisms is crucial for developing targeted therapies for insulin resistance. While multiple pathways contribute to insulin resistance, inflammatory signalling appears to be particularly important in skeletal muscle, which is responsible for approximately 80% of insulin-stimulated glucose disposal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Insulin resistance in skeletal muscle is primarily mediated by inflammatory cytokines that inhibit insulin receptor substrate proteins.","Inflammatory mediators like TNF-alpha activate serine kinases that phosphorylate and inhibit insulin receptor substrate proteins.","Multiple mechanisms contribute to insulin resistance, including lipotoxicity, endoplasmic reticulum stress, and mitochondrial dysfunction."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288","Galicia-Garcia U, Benito-Vicente A, Jebari S, Larrea-Sebal A, Siddiqi H, Uribe KB, Ostolaza H, Mart\u00edn C. Pathophysiology of Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus. Int J Mol Sci. 2020 Aug 30;21(17):6275. doi: 10.3390/ijms21176275. PMID: 32872570; PMCID: PMC7503727","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64206"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17915"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64206","l